					<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Mythical beings, demi-gods, in Indian religions</div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article is about Asura in Indian religions. For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Asura_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="Asura (disambiguation)">Asura (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Angkor_Wat_Dritte_Galerie_22_corrected.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Angkor_Wat_Dritte_Galerie_22_corrected.jpg/300px-Angkor_Wat_Dritte_Galerie_22_corrected.jpg" decoding="async" width="300" height="168" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Angkor_Wat_Dritte_Galerie_22_corrected.jpg/450px-Angkor_Wat_Dritte_Galerie_22_corrected.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Angkor_Wat_Dritte_Galerie_22_corrected.jpg/600px-Angkor_Wat_Dritte_Galerie_22_corrected.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1920" data-file-height="1074" /></a><figcaption>Asuras depicted in the <a href="/wiki/Samudra_Manthana" title="Samudra Manthana">Samudra Manthana</a> bas-relief from <a href="/wiki/Angkor_Wat" title="Angkor Wat">Angkor Wat</a></figcaption></figure>
